The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Emami Ltd has recorded a 36 per cent increase in profit after tax in 2004-05 at Rs 29.21 crore compared with Rs 21.59 crore in the previous year. Last year, the company had initiated a restructuring of its sales policy, following which its net sales increased marginally by 1 per cent to Rs 219.43 crore from Rs 216.13 in 2003-04. Its operating margins improved to 15.5 per cent from 12 per cent. The company has declared a dividend of 50 per cent for 2004-05.

 SBI Life Insurance Company has reported a 166 per cent growth in its total premium income at Rs 601 crore for 2004-05, up from Rs 225 crore in the previous fiscal. The company?s business from bancassurance channels contributed 67 per cent to its total premium income. The insurer?s new premium income grew 138 per cent to Rs 482 crore compared with Rs 202 crore in the previous year. 

 Orient Paper and Industries Ltd has been awarded a Two-star Export House certificate by the joint director general of foreign trade, ministry of commerce, for the period between April 2004 and March 2009. Following this, the company will be able to retain 100 per cent of its export earnings in foreign currency. The company has exported more than Rs 100 crore in last three years. 

 Parryware, a part of the Rs 6,200-crore Murugappa Group, has forayed into the bathroom fittings and accessories market in Calcutta with the launch of a range of taps and fittings. The Parryware taps are priced between Rs 3,000 and Rs 18,000. The company is eyeing 15 per cent of the Rs 1,000-crore domestic taps market.

 HDFC Standard Life has posted a 130.5 per cent rise in the total premium income at Rs 687 crore for the year ended march 31, 2005 against Rs 298 crore in 2003-04. The company generated new business premium income of Rs 486 crore in 2004-05, registering a year-on-year growth of 132 per cent. The growth was primarily driven by the success of the companys initiative on structured sales processes based on customer needs and their assessments.

 The International Finance Corporation has committed up to $4 million to APIDC Biotechnology Fund, a private equity fund formed to invest in start-up and early stage life science businesses in India. This is the first fund to focus exclusively on health care, drug discovery, agriculture and dairy.

 Graphite India has posted a marginal dip in income from operations at Rs 545.96 crore in 2004-05 compared with Rs 549.30 crore in the previous year. Net profit was lower at Rs 48 crore against Rs 51.32 crore in 2003-04. It has acquired the assets of Germany-based Conradty Group, a graphite electrodes manufacturing company.

